MongoDB README

Welcome to MongoDB!

COMPONENTS

  mongod - The database process.
  mongos - Sharding controller.
  mongo  - The database shell (uses interactive javascript).

UTILITIES

  mongodump         - MongoDB dump tool - for backups, snapshots, etc..
  mongorestore      - MongoDB restore a dump
  mongoexport       - Export a single collection to test (JSON, CSV)
  mongoimport       - Import from JSON or CSV
  mongofiles        - Utility for putting and getting files from MongoDB GridFS
  mongostat         - Show performance statistics

INSTALLING
  1. Update your system into newest version :
    sudo apt-get update
  2. Install required libraries :
    sudo apt-get install build-essential libboost-filesystem-dev libboost-program-options-dev libboost-system-dev libboost-thread-dev scons libboost-all-dev python-pymongo git
  3. Run scons (this may take several hours) :
    sudo scons
  4. Run the installation codes (once again it also take few hours) :
    sudo scons --prefix=/opt/mongo install
  5. Permissions for users and groups : 
    sudo adduser --firstuid 100 --ingroup nogroup --shell /etc/false --disabled-password --gecos "" --no-create-home mongodb
  6. A folder for our log files to go : 
    sudo mkdir /var/log/mongodb/
  7. Permissions for log file :
    sudo chown mongodb:nogroup /var/log/mongodb/
  8. A folder for our state data :
    sudo mkdir /var/lib/mongodb
  9. Permissions for the folder : 
    sudo chown mongodb:nogroup /var/lib/mongodb
  10. Moving our init.d script to etc:
    sudo cp debian/init.d /etc/init.d/mongod
  11. Moving our config file to etc:
    sudo cp debian/mongodb.conf /etc/
  12. Linking folders up:
    sudo ln -s /opt/mongo/bin/mongod /usr/bin/mongod
  13. Make sure the init.d script is executable and complete the installation:
    sudo chmod u+x /etc/init.d/mongod
    sudo update-rc.d mongod defaults
  14. We can now start MongoDB using the following command:
    sudo /etc/init.d/mongod start
    
